Commentary.Commentary: We are all set for the action to resume with the first innings of the Kiwis. Tom Latham and Devon Conway are the two openers for New Zealand while Shoriful Islam will bowl the first over for the hosts.
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Well, that's a wrap to the first innings of the host as the Kiwi restricts the Bangladesh innings to 172 runs. Batters of Bangladesh would be gutted as a few did get some start but couldn't capitalize and go on the score a big one. The conditions and the surface assisted the bowlers and the Kiwi bowlers made the most of it with the spinners sharing 8 wickets amongst themselves while Tim Southee took a wicket and Mushfiqur Rahim who top-scored with 35 runs was out bizarrely while obstructing the field. The surface wouldn't be an easy one for the Kiwis to bat on and with the quality of spin on offer from the Bangla Tigers, we are in for a thrilling closure to Day 1.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Tim Southee finishes things off for the Kiwis! He finishes with one wicket without giving away any runs in his spell. He lands this on a hard length and outside off, Shoriful Islam has a poke at it but gets a slight outside edge as the ball goes behind where Tom Blundell pouches it low to his front. No one appeals but the keeper looks confident and the umpire sends it upstairs. After a few replays, the third umpire is satisfied that the gloves are underneath the ball.and it is Out. Bangladesh have been bowled out for 172!

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the final session of Day 1! The umpires are back in the middle followed by the Kiwi fielder spreading out to their respective field positions. The Kiwi side is now into the tail of Bangladesh as Nayeem Hasan and Taijul Islam take center stage to score some key runs here for the hosts.
... Day 1, Session 3...

Another dominating session for New Zealand! Session Summary - 69 runs and 4 wickets in 30 overs. After Lunch, Mushfiqur Rahim and Shahadat Hossain took a cautious approach but were looking solid and gradually started to tick the scoreboard as well adding over 50 runs together. However, an absolute brain-fade moment from Rahim saw him throw his wicket away as he handled the ball and became the first Bangladeshi player to get out obstructing the field. Shahadat also failed to convert his start and nicked one down the leg side while Nurul Hasan also couldn't do much. Tim Southee continued to bowl maidens but it was the Birthday boy, Glenn Phillips who got a couple of wickets in this session. Mehidy Hasan who was looking good added a few crucial runs but was undone by a vicious delivery by Mitchell Santner. The Kiwis will look to wrap things up quickly after Tea while the hosts will want to score as many runs as possible before getting a chance to bowl on this turning track and make a game out of this one. Join us at 2 pm IST (8.30 am GMT) to see how the third session pans out.

Commentary.Commentary: Time for a drinks break. Bangladesh batters have batted well post-lunch as they have been watchful but have not missed an opportunity to keep the scoreboard moving. There is also a bit of an uproar in the cricketing world amongst fans regarding that Rahim's dismissal. So, let's try and clarify that. Bangladesh's captain, Najmul Hossain Shanto, is having a long chat with the fourth umpire, Tanvir Ahmed, as to HOW was Rahim out. Now, the reason for this question is - the mode of dismissal - obstructing the field. Common understanding tells us that obstructing means, coming deliberately in the path of the ball, on its way to the stumps. But was this hitting the wickets? Not unless the stumps were shifted virtually towards the wide guideline. So how is this out obstructing? This is because, since 2017, handling the ball has been part of the obstructing the field mode of dismissal. And this is what the law states - 37.1.1 Either batter is out Obstructing the field if and while the ball is in play, he/she wilfully attempts to obstruct or distract the fielding side by word or action. 37.1.2 The striker is out Obstructing the field if, in the act of receiving a ball delivered by the bowler, he/she wilfully strikes the ball with a hand not holding the bat. This will apply whether it is the first strike, a second strike, or a subsequent strike. The act of receiving the ball shall extend both to playing at the ball and to striking the ball more than once in defence of his/her wicket. So the confusion is because of that change in rule since 2017. I guess, the best way would be for the ICC to revert to two different modes - obstructing and handling. But that is our opinion. You are free to express yours.

OUT! OBSTRUCTING THE FIELD! A brain-fade moment for Mushfiqur Rahim as he becomes the first Bangladeshi batter to be out in this fashion. Kyle Jamieson lands this on a hard length and around off, Mushfiqur Rahim stays in his crease and bunts it out as the ball bounces off the ground and Rahim casually flicks the ball away using his hands. He did not need to do that as the ball was nowhere near the stumps. New Zealand players appeal and the umpires after a chat send it upstairs. The replay shows that he has deliberately handled the ball and he has to make that long walk back to the hut. New Zealand have been gifted a breakthrough here!

The bowling from the Kiwis was lethal and exactly what the conditions and the pitch demanded. They hit the right spots and got the better of the Bangla batters. The hard work was done by the pacers who gave away nothing to the batter and was cashed in by the spinners as they picket up wickets after their introduction. Ajaz Patel and Mitchell Santner have share four wickets equally. The season belonged to the visitors and they would be looking to wrap up this Bangladesh innings in a hurry from here on. Do catch us with the ball-to-ball coverage post-lunch at 11.40 am IST (6.10 am GMT)

After winning the toss and electing to bat first, things did not go as planned for the hosts as they lost 4 wickets in the first session with just 80 runs on board. The pitch had a lot on offer for the bowlers and the Kiwis made the most of it. The innings started with a cautious approach from both openers who struggled for a while and then departed in a quick succession. Mahmudul Hasan Joy did get the start he needed but couldn't build on it and departed on 14 while the poor run continued for Zakir Hasan. Mominul Haque too faltered but the big moment was the wicket of Najmul Hossain Shanto as he attempted a reverse sweep and was adjudged L.B.W. after a brilliant review by the Kiwis. It was then on the experienced head of Mushfiqur Rahim to build up something for the side along with Shahadat Hossain as they continued to proceed with their gritty nature and started scoring after a scrappy start.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set to begin Day 1! The two umpires make their way out in the middle followed by the New Zealand players who spread out to take their respective field positions. Mahmudul Hasan Joy and Zakir Hasan are the two openers for Bangladesh. Tim Southee has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...

Tim Southee, the captain of New Zealand says they would have batted first as well. Adds that it gets tougher to bat last in this part of the world. Tells that Kane Williamson has been unbelievable for them for a long time while Daryl Mitchell and Glenn Phillips have also contributed well. Says there are other batters as well who are hungry for runs. Informs they have made one change as Mitchell Santner comes in for Ish Sodhi.

Najmul Hossain Shanto, the skipper of Bangladesh says that they will bat first. Adds that it is a fresh wicket and they will do well if the batters take responsibility. Tells that they performed well in the last game but this is a new game and if they bat well, they should not have any problems here. Informs they are unchanged.

PITCH REPORT - HD Ackerman is pitchside. He says that it is overcast and there is a bit of moisture around which could help the seamers early on. Tells that there are a lot of grass cuttings but he expects there to be grip for the spinners. Says that all is not lost if you are batting second but ensure that you are chasing something not that big as the surface will get worse as the game progresses.

Saqlain Mushtaq, the spin bowling consultant for New Zealand is up for a chat. He says that the side should have been a bit more patient while bowling as they need to bowl on a particular spot for a longer duration to extract something from the surface. Adds that he praises the Bangladeshi side for being patient enough as they bowled really well. Mentions that he has shared his thoughts with the batting unit as well in order to how a spinner thinks on such a track.

New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham, Devon Conway, Kane Williamson, Henry Nicholls, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Glenn Phillips, Mitchell Santner (Replaces Ish Sodhi), Kyle Jamieson, Tim Southee (C), Ajaz Patel.

Bangladesh (Playing XI) - Mahmudul Hasan Joy, Zakir Hasan, Najmul Hossain Shanto (C), Mominul Haque, Mushfiqur Rahim, Shahadat Hossain, Mehidy Hasan, Nurul Hasan (WK), Nayeem Hasan, Taijul Islam, Shoriful Islam.
TOSS - Bangladesh have won the coin flip and they have decided to BAT first.

New Zealand on the other hand had an ordinary game with the batting line-up faltering massively. Runs were hard to score for their batters and It was only for Kane Williamson who scored a century in the first inning along with contributions from Daryl Mitchell and Glenn Phillips. Nothing significant came from the others. Ish Sodhi had an off-game where the conditions favored the spinners. Also, the decision to not pick Rachin Ravindra backfired as he would've been a solid pick with his all-around abilities on that turning track. The Kiwis need to buckle up and bring out their A-game if they are to level the series against the Bangla Tigers. Stay tuned for toss and team updates...

Bangladesh would be buzzing after a dominating performance in the first game where they won by 150 runs. In the first game spinner Taijul Islam was simply sensational with the ball in his hands as he took a 10-wicket haul to help his side to a victory.  There were solid batting performances from the centurion skipper Najmul Hossain Shanto along with Mahmudul Hasan Joy and Mushfiqur Rahim while Mehidy Hasan contributed with both bat and ball in both innings.. There were contributions from every player for Bangladesh and that collectively helped the hosts to clinch a victory. The side though would be looking for a bit more contribution from Zakir Hasan as he failed to make an impression of any sort in the first game. The hosts would be aiming to replicate their first-game heroics and win a historic series against the Kiwis.

Hello and welcome to all our viewers tuning in as we build up to the 2nd Test of this 2-match series between Bangladesh and New Zealand. Shere Bangla National Stadium, Mirpur, Dhaka will host this match.
...MATCH DAY...

We are back with the second innings of Bangladesh. The match officials have made their way to the center followed by the players of New Zealand who spread out to their respective field positions. Mahmudul Hasan Joy and Zakir Hasan are the openers for Bangladesh while, Ajaz Patel will bowl the first over of the second innings for New Zealand.
... THIRD INNINGS ...

The Kiwi inning comes to an end as they have scored 180 in their first innings. Well, the visitors started on a sorrowful note as they were 5 down on 46 but with a resolute batting performance majorly from Glenn Phillips along with significant contributions from others this morning the visitors have managed to cut short the gap between them and the hosts and lead them by 8 runs. Once play resumed this morning after a washout on Day 2 it was all about the Glenn Phillips show as he had only one thing in his mind and that was to tonk the ball to all the corners of the park. He kept losing wickets on the other end but did not change his approach and kept on scoring at a blistering pace on a surface that had a lot of assistance for the bowlers. Glenn Phillips played an absolute gem of a knock scoring 87 runs. The bowling from the hosts was good to start with but since morning today they were taken to the cleaners by Glenn Phillips in particular. Mehidy Hasan and Taijul Islam were the top performers with the ball they took 3 wickets each while others chipped in with wickets as well. A key session awaits us all as the ball is doing a bit and it would be interesting to see how the Bangladeshi batters approach their second innings. We will be back with the 2nd innings of Bangladesh in a short while.

With the Kiwi innings coming to an end Tea on Day 3 has been taken by the match officials. A solid recovery from 46/5 to 180 in the first innings helped the Kiwis to gain a lead of 8 runs against Bangladesh. After 4 sessions being washed out with action finally on Day 3 it was a treat for the lovers of the game with the way Glenn Phillips batted. A brilliant move by skipper Najmul Hossain Shanto of introducing Shoriful Islam in overcast conditions worked in favor of the hosts as well. Overall a brilliant passage of play from both sides was a treat for the spectators.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set to start Day 3! The sun has broken out after a long time in Dhaka and the Bangladeshi players make their way out in the middle and spread out to take their respective field positions. The revised session timings are that Tea will be taken at 1.40 pm IST (8.10 am GMT) and Stumps will be at 4.45 pm IST (11.15 am GMT) barring any further rain. Glenn Phillips and Daryl Mitchell to continue the innings for New Zealand while Taijul Islam will finish his incomplete over. Let's play...

UPDATE - 10.45 am IST (5.15 am GMT) - We have an update that would please the cricketing fans as there is scheduled inspection at 11 am IST (5.30 am GMT) with a view to to start the match at 11.30 am IST (6 am GMT). Also, Early Lunch on Day 3 has been taken. Stick with us for more news.

UPDATE - 10.30 am IST (5 am GMT) - We are inching closer to a start on Day 3 as the stumps are being installed. The players of both sides could be seen doing their respective warm-up drills. The match officials are out in the middle for an inspection and are assessing conditions while having a close look at a few patches near the square. Umpires Rod Tucker and Paul Riffel are having a brief discussion with the groundstaff as they seem unhappy with a particular patch on the bowler's run-up.

Coach of New Zealand, Luke Ronchi is up for a quick chat and says that it has been a tough tour so far for the Kiwis. Adds that they are not used to such conditions as back in New Zealand it's green wickets with bounce on offer and it's spinning here but that's the challenge international cricket throws to you. Mentions that the side must adapt in such conditions and play to what's in front of them against a quality spin bowling attack. Adds that the side has shown character and is putting in the hard yards in the practice sessions. Also adds that they have been in the subcontinent a bit recently and have an understanding of the turning tracks and would be looking to put the Bangladeshi bowlers under some pressure with an attacking mindset. Also mentions that the seamers have bowled less but that's purely on what the surface is offering, the pacers did bowl on Day 1 when it was overcast and there was assist for the pacers and looking at the conditions now the pitch would surely by a bit tacky with grip and uneven bounce on offer so they would be planning as per that.

UPDATE - 9.26 am IST (3.56 am GMT) - A positive sight from the ground as the covers have been moved out completely with the ground staff working to get the outfield playable in full swing now. An inspection is scheduled at 10.30 am IST (5 am GMT)

UPDATE - 8.55 am IST (3.25 am GMT) - Some positive news coming from the middle. The rain has stopped and the covers are off now. It is about getting the  ground ready to play there but we can see that there is little to no movement from the groundstaff, so the wait continues...

UPDATE - 8.38 am IST (3.08 am GMT) - Not the news we were hoping for but it is drizzling in a Dhaka and the covers are firmly on. It does not look like we will be getting an early start as the waiting game starts again. Stay tuned for further updates.

It was absolute chaos on Day 1 as 15 wickets fell in total. The wicket was turning right from the start and Bangladesh could only manage to score 172 runs with the Kiwi spinning trio of Mitchell Santner, Ajaz Patel, and Glenn Phillips making the most of the conditions. They would have been happy with their efforts but the Bangla Tigers showed their quality as well and Mehidy Hasan and Taijul Islam got rid of half of the New Zealand team as they lead by 117 runs. The visitors will be hoping that Daryl Mitchell and Glenn Phillips take them out of this position to get back in the game. The weather forecast remains overcast but chances of rain are less and we should be getting a lot of action on the field from now on in this Test.

Hello and welcome to our coverage of Day 3 of this exciting 2nd Test between Bangladesh and New Zealand. After rain played spoilsport on Day 2 which was washed out without a ball being bowled, the teams will look to come out on Day 3 and stamp their authority in this game. The hosts are well ahead in the game and will want to take even more control of this game while the Kiwis will hope to show some fightback and make the 'Moving Day' theirs to stay in the Test.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

The inevitable has happened! The umpires have decided to call off Day 2 where the rain gods did not show any mercy and we did not get to see any action. The match stands at the same point as New Zealand still trails by 117 runs with only five wickets in hand while Bangladesh are in a solid position and has a firm grip. Both sides will look to come up with different plans and tactics and get control of the game as we move to the 'Moving Day' of this Test. Day 3 will start early due to all the lost overs and time. The first ball will be bowled at 8.45 am IST (3.15 am GMT), but you can join us early for all the build-up. Cheers!

UPDATE - 1.02 pm IST (7.32 am GMT) - The rain eased off for a brief period of time but has now picked up the pace again and it does not look like we are going to get any action in the second session as well. Stick with us for more news.

UPDATE - 11.33 am IST (6.03 am GMT) - The first session has been washed out due to persistent rain and with the visual available it would be safe to say that even the second session of the day will be delayed.
UPDATE - 10.31 am IST (5.01 am GMT) - Nothing new to update as the covers are firmly spread out in the ground with everyone waiting for rain to ease.
UPDATE - 9.23 am IST (3.53 am GMT) - The rain is persistent, in fact it has gotten a bit earlierand everyone including the ground staff are indoors. We are in for long delay here.

UPDATE - 8.47 am IST (3.17 am GMT) - Just the news that we didn't want. It is currently drizzling in Dhaka and the start of Day 2 has been delayed. Hopefully it is just a passing shower and we get to see the teams in action as soon as possible. Stay tuned for further updates.

Day 2 has a lot to offer and looking at how the first day went it would be safe to call it a Moving Day of this Test match as a lot could happen to dictate the course of this game today. Kiwi Batter Daryl Mitchell and Glenn Phillips looked positive during their stay in the middle on Day 1 and it seems they would continue in the same manner with the pitch spinning to and fro. There is a fair bit of rain expected here so let us see how the things pans out to here. With a lot of overs lost on the first Day, we are in for an early start than scheduled to cover up for the lost overs.

Well, Day 1 belonged to the bowlers with 15 wickets falling in a shortened day due to bad light on a surface under conditions that favored the bowlers massively. After winning the toss and electing to bat first, it was a horrific batting display from the hosts that saw them bundle out for 172 which then looked below par against a side as solid as the Kiwis. Spinners shared 8 wickets amongst them while Tim Southee took a solitary wicket and Mushfiqur Rahim was adjudged obstructing the field on 35 runs as he handled a delivery. There were contributions from Shahadat Hossain, Mehidy Hasan, and others as well but no batter went on to score big to give the hosts a solid first-inning total. With the idea of gaining a massive lead in the game the Kiwi batters walked out then but little did they know what the Bangladesh bowlers had in store for them. The bowling from Bangladesh was spot on as they hit the right areas from the word go and in the blink of an eye the visitors were 5 down for 55 before stumps were called on Day 1 by the umpires due to inappropriate visibility.
...DAY 2, Session 1...

Right then, that is it from this riveting Day 1 of this 2nd Test where Bangladesh have used their home conditions well and are in control of this game even after a disappointing batting outing. The Kiwis will look to stage a fightback with the bat or else this could get away from them in a blink of an eye. We will have an early start to Day 2 as we lost a few overs here. It will begin at 8.30 am IST(3 am GMT), but you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

New Zealand, on the other hand, were in control of the game as their bowlers did an amazing job of restricting the hosts to a low score. Tim Southee was excellent and did not give away any runs and picked up a wicket in his 5.2 overs. The decision to play Mitchell Santner also proved to be fruitful as he picked up three wickets while Birthday boy, Glenn Phillips also got three scalps with Ajaz Patel getting a couple but being a bit expensive too. The Kiwis would have been happy before coming on to bat, but after a breezy start, it all went downhill for them. Their batters fell like nine pins as they have already lost half their side and all the responsibility now rests on the shoulders of Daryl Mitchell and Glenn Phillips is they want to get close to the Bangladeshi total.

Bangladesh decided to bat first but their batters couldn't really get going at all on this turning track. The openers failed to make much impact while skipper Najmul Hossain Shanto also was dismissed cheaply as they lost four wickets in the first session itself. Mushfiqur Rahim and Shahadat Hossain saw it out till Lunch. It was their partnership of more than 50 runs that steadied their ship. However, in the second session Rahim lost all his focus and handled the ball to get out which started a bit of a collapse for them as they were bowled out for 172 runs. They knew that this wicket will help their spinners and that is exactly what happened in the last session where Taijul Islam set the tone for them by getting rid of Devon Conway, and after that it was all Mehidy Hasan who picked up three wickets in no time including Kane Williamson's where the credit also must go to Shahadat Hossain for an outstanding catch at short. Taijul ended with two while bad light forced the umpires to call Stumps. The hosts will be licking their fingers to expose the Kiwi lower order early on Day 2 and bowl them out.

STUMPS ON DAY 1 DUE TO BAD LIGHT! The umpires concluded that light is not enough to continue and we end Day 1 with a dramatic twist in the third session which saw the Bangla Tigers roar back in this game. New Zealand dominated the first two sessions with the ball but it is their batting once again that has let them down and they will need someone to step up big time to take them out of this troubling situation when play resumes on Day 2.

... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Bangladesh's second innings ended on 144, and the Kiwis would now require 137 runs to level the series. After carrying on from the overnight score of 30/2 Bangladesh's innings were dealt blows regularly with the side being bundled out on 144. Zakir Hasan was brilliant with his 59-run knock on a surface that was not at all easy to bat on. His aggressive approach worked in favor of him and the hosts. Wickets kept tumbling on the other end with only 4 batters crossing the double-figure mark.  A handy 16-run partnership for the 10th wicket must give the hosts some momentum as those could well turn out to be crucial runs in this low-scoring affair. Ajaz Patel stuck to his plans and found the right spot as he was rewarded with a 5-wicket haul as he took6 well helped by Mitchell Santner who took 3 and Tim Southee took a wicket as well.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set to begin Day 4! The two umpires are making their way out in the middle now followed by the New Zealand players who spread out to take their respective field positions. Zakir Hasan and Mominul Haque are the two overnight batters for Bangladesh. Ajaz Patel to start proceedings with the ball. Let's play...

PITCH REPORT - Grant Elliot is pitchside. He says that there is variable bounce and spin and the batters will find it tough. Adds that Tim Southee used the overcast conditions well and that will be important but spin will be the key to winning this game. Tells that the batters needs to be aggressive but selective as well.

Glenn Phillips, the hero for New Zealand in their first innings is up for a chat. Glenn Phillips is up for a quick chat and says that he is enjoying his bowling as that has been something he wished for and the conditions here have helped his off-spin skillset. Adds that batting was fun as he tried to stay on top of the bowlers and put them under pressure rather than play the survival game. Mentions that the batting conditions are tough and when the spinners get into their groove it is difficult to just stay in the middle and survive so the best option is to attack.

In their second innings, Bangladesh faced an early setback as Ajaz Patel removed Mahmudul Hasan Joy in the first over itself. Despite shaky moments, Zakir Hasan and skipper Najmul Hossain Shanto showed promise before Tim Southee disrupted their plans and sent the skipper Najmul Hossain Shanto back to the hut. Bangladesh found themselves struggling and in trouble losing two wickets in quick intervals. Stalled by bad light, Stumps were called with Bangladesh leading by 30 runs at 2 wickets. As Day 4 begins, the question lingers, Can Mominul Haque and Zakir Hasan establish a resilient partnership against the formidable Kiwi bowling attack, or will the aggressive New Zealand bowlers strike early? Stay tuned for an action-packed day 4 with us.

Good morning and welcome to Day 4 of the thrilling Second Test between Bangladesh and New Zealand in Dhaka. After a rain-interrupted Day 2, New Zealand resumed at 55/5, with Glenn Phillips and Daryl Mitchell rebuilding the New Zealand innings after early setbacks. Nayeem Hasan dismissed Daryl Mitchell, but Glenn Phillips stood firm, scoring a crucial 87. He was partnered briefly by Kyle Jamieson's quick 20. Bangladesh's bowlers, led by Taijul Islam and Mehidy Hasan, kept the pressure on, both shared 3 wickets each. Shoriful Islam and Nayeem Hasan chipped in by plucking two each as well. Consequently, New Zealand struggled to extend their lead and got all out on a mere 180 and slightly crept ahead of the hosts by only 8 runs.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Right then, that is it from this shortened but exciting Day 3 of the 2nd Test. It is called the 'Moving Day' and the game has moved nicely but there is nothing in between the teams at the moment. New Zealand will hope to make early inroads on Day 4 while Bangladesh will look for a partnership to get ahead in the game. We will once again have an early start due to the lost time and overs as Day 4 will begin on 9th December, Saturday at 8.30 am IST (3 am GMT), but as you know you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

Bangladesh, on the other hand, would have been a tad bit disappointed with not bowling the Kiwis out earlier than they did. They managed to reduce them to 97-7 but had no answers to the counter-attacking batting from Glenn Phillips. Najmul Hossain Shanto was good with his bowling changes once again as once he brought Nayeem Hasan in the attack, he sent Daryl Mitchell and Mitchell Santner back in quick succession. Shoriful Islam eventually managed to get Phillips out but the damage was already done by then and Taijul Islam wrapped things up for them. They couldn't get off to a good start as Mahmudul Hasan Joy lost his wicket in the very first over of their second innings. Zakir Hasan looked solid and steadied things for them along with Shanto, but their skipper took a painful blow on his bottom hand and could not stick around for long after that as Bangladesh ended the Day with a slight lead. The responsibility lies on the shoulders of Zakir Hasan and Mominul Haque to extend it and set up a good target.

New Zealand started Day 3 on the front foot with Glenn Phillips taking an attacking approach and finding the boundaries to put pressure on the hosts. Daryl Mitchell though lost his wicket trying to be aggressive but Phillips did not change his plans. He missed out on a well-deserved hundred and was dismissed for 87 but his knock along with good contributions from Tim Southee and Kyle Jamieson helped the Kiwis to take a lead of 7 runs. Ajaz Patel set the tone for them by picking up a wicket on the very first over after Tea while Tim Southee got rid of the wounded Bangladeshi skipper, Shanto before bad light stopped play and we could not get any more action.

STUMPS ON DAY 3 DUE TO BAD LIGHT! The news we were expecting and the umpires have deemed that the light is not enough here. A closely fought Day 3 comes to a premature end! Firstly, it was the rain that delayed the start of the proceedings and towards the end bad light once again forced Stumps. However, even with those factors, there was no shortage of entertainment as at the start of the Day, Glenn Phillips played a fiery knock which helped the visitors take a small lead, but Bangladesh overcame it and are leading by 30 runs with the loss of two wickets and will look to extend it further when they come out to bat again.

Commentary.Commentary: Righ then, that is it from this enthralling Test match and this series as well where Bangladesh and New Zealand share the spoils. The trophy has been handed to both captains, Tim Southee and Najmul Hossain Shanto who join their teams and both sides pose together for the pictures. These two sides now travel to New Zealand to meet again in a three-match ODI series. The first game will be played on 17th December, Sunday starting at 3.30 am IST (10 pm GMT, Previous Day), but as you know you can always join us early for all the build-up to the game. Until then, cheers and goodbye!

Tim Southee, the victorious skipper of New Zealand says it was a bit tough, but he's happy they ended up winning. Adds that the team trusted their skills, and on this pitch, you can play your way. Credits Bangladesh as well. Tells that it was just a matter of time before wickets fell. Says it's not easy when people expect quick results, Ajaz Patel did great with six wickets, and winning on a pitch like this feels really good.

Taijul Islam is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES for his 15 wickets in two Tests. He says that the side played well and he would've been much more delighted with this award had it come in a winning cause. Adds that the side played well overall but they needed a few more runs in this game.

Glenn Phillips is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his stellar all-around performance. He says that at the end of the day, runs always mattered on such a track and thankfully they got more than the opponents here. Adds that Tim Southee created pressure early on and then the spinners cleared up the batting unit of the opponents restricting them to a low total that worked in their favor. Mentions that he just sticks to his plans and tries to put the bowler under pressure and sometimes it clicks and at times it doesn't, but the approach will remain the same. Also credits Santner for his batting heroics at the end.

Najmul Hossain Shanto, the captain of Bangladesh says that their bowlers did an awesome job, all four of them. Adds that he is proud of how everyone helped in the field. Tells that in the first match, they played well, but in the latest one, missed some chances and will look to learn from it. Says that now they are getting ready for the ODI series in New Zealand, and hopes everyone plays great there too. He emphasized the importance of teamwork and staying positive for the upcoming challenges.
Presentation Time...

New Zealand, on the other hand, also struggled in their first innings as even after a breezy start, they lost half their side before Stumps on Day 1 which saw 15 wickets fall in total. Taijul Islam and Mehidy Hasan spun a web around them while Shahadat Hossain took a stunner to dismiss the main man, Kane Williamson. We did not get any action on Day 2 due to consistent rain which was a bit of a disappointment. However, on Day 3 we saw Glenn Phillips taking an attacking approach and putting pressure on the bowlers by hitting boundaries. He played a fantastic knock of 83 runs missing out on a hundred while Tim Southee and Kyle Jamieson helped them to take a first innings lead of 8 runs. Just like the Kiwis, it was the spin trio of Taijul, Mehidy, and Nayeem Hasan who shared eight wickets while Shoriful Islam also bowled well and picked up a couple. After that, we could not get much action but the Kiwis were able to pick up two wickets with the crucial one being of Najmul Hossain Shanto who gave in to a hostile spell from Southee. Then bad light stopped play just like in Day 1 and the hosts ended with a 30-run lead going into Day 4. In the end, New Zealand kept their calm, and with the inspired selection of Mitchell Santner and Phillips' brilliance shared the spoils in this series.

Bangladesh once again decided to bat first after winning the toss as this was another rank-turner of a wicket. Their openers once again failed to make any impact as they were already four down in the first session. It was the partnership between Mushfiqur Rahim and Shahadat Hossain that steadied things for them. However, the talking point in the second session was the dismissal of Rahim as he handled the ball deliberately and became the first Bangladeshi batter to be out 'obstructing the field'. After that, some handy contributions from Mehidy Hasan and Nurul Hasan took them to a total of 172 runs. Tim Southee bowled well in the overcast conditions and gave away no runs in his 5.2 overs and picked up a wicket but it was the trip of Ajaz Patel, Mitchell Santner, and Glenn Phillips did the rest of the job quite effectively with the Phillips taking three wickets on his birthday.

Bangladeshi batters were all over the place from the start of Day 4 but a fighting half-century from opener Zakir Hasan and important runs from Shoriful Islam and Taijul Islam in the end helped them set a target of 137 runs. Ajaz Patel shone with a six-wicket haul for the Kiwis. While chasing, New Zealand's top order once again had no answers to the spin prowess of Bangladesh and they were in a spot of trouble with 51/5 on the scoreboard. However, Tom Latham played a good knock before getting out while Daryl Mitchell also added some important runs. The Kiwis needed 47 runs with four wickets in hand after Tea and it was that man, Glenn Phillips, who impressed with the bat after getting an early life as he was dropped by Najmul Hossain Shanto. He along with Mitchell Santner dodged a few close calls and with a partnership of 70 runs took them over the line.

BLACKCAPS WINS A THRILLER AND LEVELS THE SERIES! What an exceptional Test match this has been! We saw absolutely everything and even rain and bad light could not stop this match from getting a result. This game went back and forth as both teams genuinely had a chance of getting the win at different points, but it was the all-round show from Glenn Phillips that proved to be the difference as the Kiwis avenged their defeat in the first Test.

An eventful session comes to an end! The match is nicely poised and the equation is simple now as New Zealand needs 47 runs to win while Bangladesh requires four wickets. After Lunch, Devon Conway could not hang around for long as Shoriful Islam got the early breakthrough for the hosts. Kane Williamson who looked solid as well was removed by a beauty from Taijul Islam. That was followed by a mini collapse as they were reduced to 51/5. Tom Latham held one end and scored crucial 26 runs but his resistance was broken as well. Daryl Mitchell showed his experience and used the sweeps and reverse sweeps well but it also led to his downfall. Glenn Phillips was dropped early in his innings by Najmul Hossain Shanto and he will want to make the most out of it. Mehidy Hasan was the pick of the bowlers with three wickets while Taijul got two but was expensive in the session and they will look to add more after Tea and take the hosts over the line. Bangladesh knew they would have to take wickets and keep the dot ball percentage high to put any sort of pressure on the Kiwis with them chasing a mere 137 to level the series. The bowlers were spot-on with their lines and lengths and bowled outstandingly. A couple of overs from the tall pacer Shoriful Islam were too hot to handle for the Kiwi opener as he came close to taking a wicket at the very least several times. With the visitors being 4 for no loss they require 133 runs more to level the series.  A perfect setup with a decisive session awaiting us all in the context of this game and the series. Let's see what unfolds in the post-lunch session as we will be back by 11.40 am IST (6.10 am GMT).

It is time for Lunch on Day 4 as the Kiwis are required to chase 137 to level the series. The day started with Bangladesh hoping to bat deep in the day and posting a total above 200 at least which would have been a big ask for the Kiwis but the persistent line and length from the Kiwi bowlers brought wickets regularly and the Bangladesh was cut short on 144. Zakir Hasan continued his good form from yesterday and kept the dancing shoes on as he used the crease to maximum effect and managed to score 59 before being dismissed. Ajaz Patel was by daylight the best bowler for the Kiwi as he scalped 6 wickets while Mitchell Santner grabbed 3 and Tim Southee took a wicket as well.
